{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"024f88cf-4de9-470c-be4f-eb5fab673059","content":"Here's the correct skip attribute for each framework:\n\n| Framework | Attribute | Example |\n|-----------|-----------|---------|\n| **MSTest** | `[Ignore(\"reason\")]` | `[TestMethod, Ignore(\"Bug #123\")]` |\n| **xUnit** | `[Fact(Skip = \"reason\")]` | `[Fact(Skip = \"Bug #123\")]` |\n| **NUnit** | `[Ignore(\"reason\")]` | `[Test, Ignore(\"Bug #123\")]` |\n| **TUnit** | `[Skip(\"reason\")]` | `[Test, Skip(\"Bug #123\")]` |\n\n**Notes:**\n- **xUnit theories**: use `[Theory(Skip = \"reason\")]` — the `Skip` property is on the test attribute itself, not a separate attribute.\n- **MSTest & NUnit**: `[Ignore]` is a standalone attribute applied alongside `[TestMethod]`/`[Test]`.\n- **TUnit**: uses `[Skip]` rather than `[Ignore]`.\n\nAll four frameworks support a reason string, which shows up in test runner output so your team knows *why* a test was skipped.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"212830d1-e685-4337-a397-7c7554f6b0a0","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about the correct skip/ignore attributes for each test framework. Let me use the dotnet-test-frameworks skill which has reference data for skip annotations across MSTest, xUnit, NUnit, and TUnit.","outputTokens":335,"requestId":"340B:1B2DC6:A52E62:C1B552:69F3FF51"},"id":"ee07f825-f1d7-4899-acfb-11342416e33c","timestamp":"2026-05-01T01:18:17.051Z","parentId":"65cf6ddb-e61a-4001-b6de-430eadf1e58c"}
